{"timestamp": "2025-12-05 03:39:13.670269", "event": "llm_end", "text": "Troubleshooting Diagnosis Report\n\nSummary of Network Health\n- Status: Unhealthy – complete data plane outage for tenant subnet 10.0.0.0/24.\n- Primary symptom: All host-to-host connectivity fails, including hosts on the same leaf switch.\n- Control-plane issue: All OVS switches are disconnected from the SDN controller and are operating in fail-close mode with no flows installed, causing all data traffic (including ARP) to be dropped.\n\nEvidence Collected\n1) End-host connectivity tests\n- Pings between hosts fail with “Destination Host Unreachable” from the source IP, even within the same leaf:\n  - host_1_1 -> host_1_2: 100% loss, “Destination Host Unreachable”\n  - host_1_1 -> host_2_1: 100% loss, “Destination Host Unreachable”\n  - host_2_1 -> host_2_2: 100% loss, “Destination Host Unreachable”\n- ARP resolution fails on hosts:\n  - host_1_1: ip neigh shows “FAILED” for 10.0.0.2 and 10.0.0.9\n- Host interfaces are up with correct IPs and routes:\n  - All hosts have 10.0.0.X/24 on eth0 and direct 10.0.0.0/24 routes.\n\n2) Switch state and configuration\n- OVS bridges exist on leaf_1, leaf_2, spine_1 with fail_mode: secure and controller set to tcp:20.0.0.100:6633.\n- OpenFlow state:\n  - ovs-ofctl dump-flows shows no flows on all switches.\n  - ovs-ofctl show indicates all physical ports are LIVE.\n- Controller connectivity status on switches:\n  - ovs-vsctl list controller shows is_connected=false; status indicates “Connection timed out”, state=CONNECTING/BACKOFF.\n- Management connectivity:\n  - All switches have management IPs on 20.0.0.0/24 (leaf_1: 20.0.0.5, leaf_2: 20.0.0.6, spine_1: 20.0.0.1).\n  - All switches successfully ping 20.0.0.100.\n  - TCP connectivity test to controller’s OpenFlow ports fails from switches:\n    - TCP connect to 20.0.0.100:6633 and 6653 returns RC:1 (cannot establish connection).\n\n3) Topology and links\n- Physical interfaces on switches are UP and reported LIVE by OVS (no indications of link failure).\n- No evidence of miswired or downed interfaces for host or leaf-spine links based on port state.\n\nAnomalies Detected\n- All tenant traffic is dropped at the switches due to an empty OpenFlow pipeline combined with fail_mode=secure.\n- All OVS switches cannot establish a TCP session to the controller at 20.0.0.100 on standard OpenFlow ports (6633/6653), despite being able to reach it via ICMP on the management network.\n- Host ARP resolution fails for peers on the same subnet, consistent with L2 flooding/broadcast being blocked due to lack of flows.\n\nFault Localization\n- Fault domain: Control plane, specifically the SDN controller endpoint at 20.0.0.100 (service/ports).\n- Data-plane devices (leaf_1, leaf_2, spine_1) appear operational at the physical/link layer and correctly configured to point to the controller, but are disconnected because the controller service is not accepting OpenFlow TCP connections.\n\nRoot Cause\n- The SDN controller at 20.0.0.100 is not listening or reachable on the OpenFlow port(s) (6633 and 6653). This results in all OVS switches remaining in fail_mode=secure with no flows installed, thereby dropping all tenant traffic (including ARP) and causing a full outage on 10.0.0.0/24.\n\nRelevant Findings\n- Controller target configured: tcp:20.0.0.100:6633 across all switches.\n- Controller connection state on switches: is_connected=false with last_error “Connection timed out”.\n- TCP connectivity tests to 20.0.0.100:6633 and 6653 fail while ICMP ping succeeds, indicating the service/port is closed or blocked rather than a general L3 path issue.\n- No flows present on switches; with secure fail mode, default behavior is to drop traffic.\n- All host NICs and switch ports appear UP without physical errors.\n\nConclusion\nThe network outage is caused by the SDN controller at 20.0.0.100 not accepting OpenFlow connections. This leaves all OVS switches in a fail-close state with empty flow tables, blocking ARP and all L2/L3 forwarding on the tenant subnet. The fault lies with the controller service/host rather than the data-plane switches or links.", "generation_info": {"finish_reason": "stop", "logprobs": null}, "invalid_tool_calls": [], "usage_metadata": {"input_tokens": 31560, "output_tokens": 2836, "total_tokens": 34396, "input_token_details": {"audio": 0, "cache_read": 31232}, "output_token_details": {"audio": 0, "reasoning": 1792}}}
